T1  - Migration, health, and socioenvironmental safety net among children of Dhaka, Bangladesh.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/19338244.2016.1254081
A1  - Molla, Neelima Afroz
A1  - Ali, Ghaffar
A1  - Mollah, Kabirul Ahsan
A1  - Wongwit, Waranya
A1  - Shipin, Oleg
A1  - Ramasoota, Pongrama
A1  - Nur, Husna Parvin
Y1  - 2017//
Y2  - 20161031//
N2  - This study quantifies the diarrhea burden among migrant children under age 5 (who have migrated due to environmental degradation) in Dhaka. We used a multifactor socioepidemiological as well as environmental approach with pretested questionnaires and observations. It was found that 52% of the children were affected by diarrhea. Disability-adjusted life years (DALYs) lost was reduced manifold with the increase of mothers' behavioral determinants. Health losses were 1,718 fold with significant coefficient (beta) in the migrant group. DALYs lost were significantly associated with socioenvironmental factors such as mother's illiteracy (beta = .18; p < .001), no hand wash before eating (beta = .08; p = .004), and no hand wash after defecation (beta = .10; p < .001). This puts emphasis clearly on the awareness at household level, especially of mothers and children under age 5 in Dhaka, Bangladesh, in formulating migration-related policies.
